grammar.body:
Each digit 0–9 is its own root word from the regular vocabulary, chosen because its meaning resonates with the number's character. Like all roots, digits are POS-neutral — they can be nouns, verbs, or modifiers.

0 = {{dict:i:d0.word}} · 1 = {{dict:i:d1.word}} · 2 = {{dict:i:d2.word}} · 3 = {{dict:i:d3.word}} · 4 = {{dict:i:d4.word}}
5 = {{dict:i:d5.word}} · 6 = {{dict:i:d6.word}} · 7 = {{dict:i:d7.word}} · 8 = {{dict:i:d8.word}} · 9 = {{dict:i:d9.word}}

In numeric expressions digits are spoken bare — no prefix. You only mark specific boundary points.
